  abstract   = {Offers recommendations to applied researchers on the use of various parametric and nonparametric alternatives to the ANOVA F test under assumption violation conditions. Meta-analytic techniques were used to summarize the statistical robustness literature on the Type I error properties of the Brown-Forsythe (M. B. Brown A. B. Forsythe, 1974), G. S. James (1951) second-order, Kruskal-Wallis (W. H. Kruskal and W. A. Wallis, 1952), and B. L. Welch (1951) tests. Two variables, based on the theoretical work of G. E. P. Box (1954), are shown to be highly effective in deciding when a particular alternative procedure should be adopted. Based on the meta-analysis findings, it is recommended that researchers gain a clear understanding of the nature of their data before conducting statistical analyses. Of all of the procedures, the James and Welch tests performed best under violations of the variance homogeneity assumption, although their sensitivity to certain types of nonnormality may preclude their use in all data-analytic situations. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
